#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:5
msgid "NumPy 2.0 migration guide"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:7
msgid ""
"This document contains a set of instructions on how to update your code to "
"work with NumPy 2.0. It covers changes in NumPy's Python and C APIs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:12
msgid ""
"Note that NumPy 2.0 also breaks binary compatibility - if you are "
"distributing binaries for a Python package that depends on NumPy's C API, "
"please see :ref:`numpy-2-abi-handling`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:19
msgid "Ruff plugin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:21
msgid ""
"Many of the changes covered in the 2.0 release notes and in this migration "
"guide can be automatically adapted in downstream code with a dedicated `Ruff "
"<https://docs.astral.sh/ruff/>`__ rule, namely rule `NPY201 <https://docs."
"astral.sh/ruff/rules/numpy2-deprecation/>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:26
msgid ""
"You should install ``ruff>=0.4.8`` and add the ``NPY201`` rule to your "
"``pyproject.toml``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:29
msgid ""
"[tool.ruff.lint]\n"
"select = [\"NPY201\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:32
msgid "You can also apply the NumPy 2.0 rule directly from the command line::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:34
msgid "$ ruff check path/to/code/ --select NPY201"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:40
msgid "Changes to NumPy data type promotion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:42
msgid ""
"NumPy 2.0 changes promotion (the result of combining dissimilar data types) "
"as per :ref:`NEP 50 <NEP50>`. Please see the NEP for details on this change. "
"It includes a table of example changes and a backwards compatibility section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:46
msgid ""
"The largest backwards compatibility change is that the precision of scalars "
"is now preserved consistently.  Two examples are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:49
msgid ""
"``np.float32(3) + 3.`` now returns a float32 when it previously returned a "
"float64."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:51
msgid ""
"``np.array([3], dtype=np.float32) + np.float64(3)`` will now return a "
"float64 array.  (The higher precision of the scalar is not ignored.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:54
msgid ""
"For floating point values, this can lead to lower precision results when "
"working with scalars.  For integers, errors or overflows are possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:57
msgid ""
"To solve this, you may cast explicitly.  Very often, it may also be a good "
"solution to ensure you are working with Python scalars via ``int()``, "
"``float()``, or ``numpy_scalar.item()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:61
msgid ""
"To track down changes, you can enable emitting warnings for changed behavior "
"(use ``warnings.simplefilter`` to raise it as an error for a traceback)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:64
msgid "np._set_promotion_state(\"weak_and_warn\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:66
msgid ""
"which is useful during testing. Unfortunately, running this may flag many "
"changes that are irrelevant in practice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:72
msgid "Windows default integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:73
msgid ""
"The default integer used by NumPy is now 64bit on all 64bit systems (and "
"32bit on 32bit system).  For historic reasons related to Python 2 it was "
"previously equivalent to the C ``long`` type. The default integer is now "
"equivalent to ``np.intp``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:78
msgid ""
"Most end-users should not be affected by this change.  Some operations will "
"use more memory, but some operations may actually become faster. If you "
"experience issues due to calling a library written in a compiled language it "
"may help to explicitly cast to a ``long``, for example with: ``arr = arr."
"astype(\"long\", copy=False)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:84
msgid ""
"Libraries interfacing with compiled code that are written in C, Cython, or a "
"similar language may require updating to accommodate user input if they are "
"using the ``long`` or equivalent type on the C-side. In this case, you may "
"wish to use ``intp`` and cast user input or support both ``long`` and "
"``intp`` (to better support NumPy 1.x as well). When creating a new integer "
"array in C or Cython, the new ``NPY_DEFAULT_INT`` macro will evaluate to "
"either ``NPY_LONG`` or ``NPY_INTP`` depending on the NumPy version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:93
msgid "Note that the NumPy random API is not affected by this change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:96
msgid "C-API Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:98
msgid ""
"Some definitions were removed or replaced due to being outdated or "
"unmaintainable.  Some new API definitions will evaluate differently at "
"runtime between NumPy 2.0 and NumPy 1.x. Some are defined in ``numpy/_core/"
"include/numpy/npy_2_compat.h`` (for example ``NPY_DEFAULT_INT``) which can "
"be vendored in full or part to have the definitions available when compiling "
"against NumPy 1.x."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:105
msgid ""
"If necessary, ``PyArray_RUNTIME_VERSION >= NPY_2_0_API_VERSION`` can be used "
"to explicitly implement different behavior on NumPy 1.x and 2.0. (The compat "
"header defines it in a way compatible with such use.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:109
msgid "Please let us know if you require additional workarounds here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:114
msgid "The ``PyArray_Descr`` struct has been changed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:115
msgid ""
"One of the most impactful C-API changes is that the ``PyArray_Descr`` struct "
"is now more opaque to allow us to add additional flags and have itemsizes "
"not limited by the size of ``int`` as well as allow improving structured "
"dtypes in the future and not burden new dtypes with their fields."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:120
msgid ""
"Code which only uses the type number and other initial fields is unaffected. "
"Most code will hopefully mainly access the ``->elsize`` field, when the "
"dtype/descriptor itself is attached to an array (e.g. ``arr->descr-"
">elsize``) this is best replaced with ``PyArray_ITEMSIZE(arr)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:125
msgid "Where not possible, new accessor functions are required:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:127
msgid ""
"``PyDataType_ELSIZE`` and ``PyDataType_SET_ELSIZE`` (note that the result is "
"now ``npy_intp`` and not ``int``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:129
msgid "``PyDataType_ALIGNMENT``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:130
msgid "``PyDataType_FIELDS``, ``PyDataType_NAMES``, ``PyDataType_SUBARRAY``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:131
msgid "``PyDataType_C_METADATA``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:133
msgid ""
"Cython code should use Cython 3, in which case the change is transparent. "
"(Struct access is available for elsize and alignment when compiling only for "
"NumPy 2.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:137
msgid ""
"For compiling with both 1.x and 2.x if you use these new accessors it is "
"unfortunately necessary to either define them locally via a macro like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:140
msgid ""
"#if NPY_ABI_VERSION < 0x02000000\n"
"  #define PyDataType_ELSIZE(descr) ((descr)->elsize)\n"
"#endif"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:144
msgid ""
"or adding ``npy2_compat.h`` into your code base and explicitly include it "
"when compiling with NumPy 1.x (as they are new API). Including the file has "
"no effect on NumPy 2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:148
msgid ""
"Please do not hesitate to open a NumPy issue, if you require assistance or "
"the provided functions are not sufficient."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:151
msgid ""
"**Custom User DTypes:** Existing user dtypes must now use :c:type:"
"`PyArray_DescrProto` to define their dtype and slightly modify the code. See "
"note in :c:func:`PyArray_RegisterDataType`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:156
msgid "Functionality moved to headers requiring ``import_array()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:157
msgid ""
"If you previously included only ``ndarraytypes.h`` you may find that some "
"functionality is not available anymore and requires the inclusion of "
"``ndarrayobject.h`` or similar. This include is also needed when vendoring "
"``npy_2_compat.h`` into your own codebase to allow use of the new "
"definitions when compiling with NumPy 1.x."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:163
msgid "Functionality which previously did not require import includes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:165
msgid ""
"Functions to access dtype flags: ``PyDataType_FLAGCHK``, "
"``PyDataType_REFCHK``, and the related ``NPY_BEGIN_THREADS_DESCR``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:167
msgid "``PyArray_GETITEM`` and ``PyArray_SETITEM``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:170
msgid ""
"It is important that the ``import_array()`` mechanism is used to ensure that "
"the full NumPy API is accessible when using the ``npy_2_compat.h`` header.  "
"In most cases your extension module probably already calls it. However, if "
"not we have added ``PyArray_ImportNumPyAPI()`` as a preferable way to ensure "
"the NumPy API is imported.  This function is light-weight when called "
"multiple times so that you may insert it wherever it may be needed (if you "
"wish to avoid setting it up at module import)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:181
msgid "Increased maximum number of dimensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:182
msgid ""
"The maximum number of dimensions (and arguments) was increased to 64. This "
"affects the ``NPY_MAXDIMS`` and ``NPY_MAXARGS`` macros. It may be good to "
"review their use, and we generally encourage you to not use these macros "
"(especially ``NPY_MAXARGS``), so that a future version of NumPy can remove "
"this limitation on the number of dimensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:188
msgid ""
"``NPY_MAXDIMS`` was also used to signal ``axis=None`` in the C-API, "
"including the ``PyArray_AxisConverter``. The latter will return "
"``-2147483648`` as an axis (the smallest integer value). Other functions may "
"error with ``AxisError: axis 64 is out of bounds for array of dimension`` in "
"which case you need to pass ``NPY_RAVEL_AXIS`` instead of ``NPY_MAXDIMS``. "
"``NPY_RAVEL_AXIS`` is defined in the ``npy_2_compat.h`` header and runtime "
"dependent (mapping to 32 on NumPy 1.x and ``-2147483648`` on NumPy 2.x)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:198
msgid "Complex types - Underlying type changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:200
msgid ""
"The underlying C types for all of the complex types have been changed to use "
"native C99 types. While the memory layout of those types remains identical "
"to the types used in NumPy 1.x, the API is slightly different, since direct "
"field access (like ``c.real`` or ``c.imag``) is no longer possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:205
msgid ""
"It is recommended to use the functions ``npy_creal`` and ``npy_cimag`` (and "
"the corresponding float and long double variants) to retrieve the real or "
"imaginary part of a complex number, as these will work with both NumPy 1.x "
"and with NumPy 2.x. New functions ``npy_csetreal`` and ``npy_csetimag``, "
"along with compatibility macros ``NPY_CSETREAL`` and ``NPY_CSETIMAG`` (and "
"the corresponding float and long double variants), have been added for "
"setting the real or imaginary part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:213
msgid ""
"The underlying type remains a struct under C++ (all of the above still "
"remains valid)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:216
msgid ""
"This has implications for Cython. It is recommended to always use the native "
"typedefs ``cfloat_t``, ``cdouble_t``, ``clongdouble_t`` rather than the "
"NumPy types ``npy_cfloat``, etc, unless you have to interface with C code "
"written using the NumPy types. You can still write cython code using the ``c."
"real`` and ``c.imag`` attributes (using the native typedefs), but you can no "
"longer use in-place operators ``c.imag += 1`` in Cython's c++ mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:223
msgid ""
"Because NumPy 2 now includes ``complex.h`` code that uses a variable named "
"``I`` may see an error such as"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:230
msgid "to use the name ``I`` requires an ``#undef I`` now."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:233
msgid ""
"NumPy 2.0.1 briefly included the ``#undef I`` to help users not already "
"including ``complex.h``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:238
msgid "Changes to namespaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../numpy_2_0_migration_guide.rst:240
msgid ""
"In NumPy 2.0 certain functions, modules, and constants were moved or removed "
"to make the NumPy namespace more user-friendly by removing unnecessary or "
"outdated functionality and clarifying which parts of NumPy are considered "
"private. Please see the tables below for guidance on migration.  For most "
"changes this means replacing it with a backwards compatible alternative."
msgstr ""

